Title: Bayesian Methods for Hackers: Probabilistic Programming and Bayesian Inference
Author: Cameron Davidson-Pilon
My Review:
Before starting the book, I thought it was trying to make statistics, and especially Bayesian statistics, easier to pick up for developers with little stats background. On the other hand, I found the discussion on Bayesian methods fairly difficult to follow, especially in the later chapters.

Also, the library PyMC3 has dependency on Theano which is now deprecated. A Tensorflow for Probability version of these chapters is available on Github and learning about that was interesting.
I did learn about some powerful new ideas and it would be interesting to see more research in this space, but for now, I don't see much use of these techniques in my day-to-day ML projects.

Title: Statistical Inference via Data Science: A ModernDive into R and the Tidyverse (Chapman & Hall/CRC The R Series)
Author: Chester Ismay
My Review: The chapters on data wrangling and visualization were just a summary of the R4DS book by Hadley Wickham. So if you have read that book, just skip to the chapters on statistics. The authors have introduced new libraries for performing statistical inference in a tidy way. The applications were too simple though. The comparison of theory vs simulation based inference methods was good, and a few more in-depth examples could have helped. Overall, it is a book targeted at beginners and is free and open source, so I can't complain much !!

My Review:
Beginners please ignore this book.

It is just a collection of Medium articles, and includes a lot of complex Java code without any introduction and context.

I thought I'll learn about industry best practises, but the only learning I got was to use Google Cloud managed services wherever possible.

You can probably skim through this book in an hour as there really is not much content to read.

Title: The Honest Thief
Author: Fyodor Dostoyevsky
My Review: This appears to be a very simple short story at first. However, it has a deeper meaning revolving around the emotional transformation of the narrator. The narrator is shown to be aloof and emotionally distant in the beginning. But through his interactions with Astafy, he seems to have developed empathy for human emotions, which leads to him narrating the story. Otherwise, there would have been no point in introducing the short plot before Astafy and Emelyan's story. I think the author wanted to imply that Astafy was able to change narrator's heart and bring him out of his shell. The narrator has been living alone for years which has made emotionally numb. However, the story of Astafy did something to the narrator which made him tell us the story.

Title: The Kite Runner
Author: Khaled Hosseini
My Review: Quite an emotional novel. The writing was really good and was filled with some brilliant dialogues. The plot was especially gripping although it was slightly stretched towards the end. A great account of what's life like in Afghanistan now, and what it used to be. What struck me the most was the brutal honesty in which the author spoke about the most uncomfortable things one could imagine. This book really lived up to the hype and expectations.

Title: Zen and the Art of Motorcycle Maintenance: An Inquiry Into Values (Phaedrus, #1)
Author: Robert M. Pirsig

Title: Cuckold
Author: Kiran Nagarkar
My Review: Great piece of imagination by the author. A very engaging and fast paced novel. Also provides you with a really good perspective on life in the royal palace in 16th century Mewar. I really liked the character of the narrator / crown prince who though appears to be so calculative in every aspect and who looks like the most unpopular guy in Mewar at that time but he has a great intellect and the gumption to do things he feels is right not just for him but for everyone else. Though Mirabai is supposed to be the central character, I could never really understand her motives or ideas. The part that deals with the war tactics and the obsession with Babur was kind of overstretched. But overall, I found it a very entertaining book and could easily imagine a big budget Bollywood movie made out of it.

Title: The Goal: A Process of Ongoing Improvement
Author: Eliyahu M. Goldratt
My Review: The book mostly deals with management topics like the theory of constraints. I think this is a very good method to teach any kind of concept in general, a kind of a fusion of education and entertainment. Wish more books could talk about the abstract ideas of management in a manner as engaging as the author did.

Title: Man's Search for Meaning
Author: Viktor E. Frankl
Additional Authors: Harold S. Kushner, William J. Winslade, Isle Lasch
My Review: Strong ideas really. Finding meaning of life in pain, hardship and struggle. I thought it was a very practical book and though it talks pain and suffering, the tone is very optimistic and it does fill you with hope and the enthusiasm to take on any challenge that life throws at you.

Title: What I Talk About When I Talk About Running
Author: Haruki Murakami
My Review: I read this book while training for a half marathon myself. It definitely motivates to go out and run for the sheer joy of it. This was my first Murakami book and I found the writing to be very fluid. I think I will try some of his more popular books very soon.

Title: Flow: The Psychology of Optimal Experience
Author: Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi
My Review: A really insightful book about psychology and philosophy. Will want to definitely go through the book once more to try and apply so many ideas that the author talks about.

Title: Madame Bovary
Author: Gustave Flaubert
Additional Authors: Mark Overstall, Paul De Man, Malcolm Bowie, Margaret Mauldon

Title: The Will to Meaning: Foundations and Applications of Logotherapy
Author: Viktor E. Frankl

Title: Attached: The New Science of Adult Attachment and How It Can Help You Find—and Keep—Love
Author: Amir Levine

Title: Emma
Author: Jane Austen
My Review: Not my cup of tea. I never really liked fiction and Emma was really a hopeless novel for me. I think I am done with Jane Austen, atleast for the near future. Their is virtually no real plot, just a bunch of characters talking and gossiping about each other. I also did not have any context of the 18th century England to appreciate the finer points of the plot. Although the language was the book's only positive and words were literally flowing freely throughout the novel, there was no real subject matter in the plot to hold my interest.

Title: Sita: An Illustrated Retelling of the Ramayana
Author: Devdutt Pattanaik
My Review: I wanted to give this book five stars initially but was disappointed by its end. There was no need to name it Sita, because her role is very limited in the book. Where the author excelled was in the level of detail in which he explored various relationships between characters. He also points out very interesting trends and anecdotes that add to the story. Overall, it's a must read for anyone interested in religion and mythology.

Title: The Prince
Author: Niccolò Machiavelli
My Review: I had heard a lot about Nicollo Machiaveli, and I must admit, at some level, I was disappointed. This book was not as scandalous as I expected. Secondly, I felt that the use of examples and case studies to prove his theories was not very effective because A. the kings and rulers from that period are neither very well known or significant B. Machiaveli throws so many names that it's difficult to keep track of them even after repeated references to glossary. Nevertheless, this book was not meant for the comman man to read. It definitely lays down some important, though debatable, theories and principles that would have proved invaluable to any ruler from that period, in some cases, even today. What kept me going was that the book was short and it was sprinkled with tiny nuggets of wisdom.

Title: The Death of Ivan Ilyich
Author: Leo Tolstoy
My Review: A very engaging narrative. Tolstoy depicts the harsh realities of life that we tend to overlook and ignore. Death is the ultimate reality.

Title: Dancing with Maharaja
Author: Sundar
My Review: An oversimplified view of the life of a UPSC aspirant. The story is filled with cliches. It maybe motivating for some, but nothing of real value here.

Title: Guyland: The Perilous World Where Boys Become Men
Author: Michael S. Kimmel

Title: Einstein: His Life and Universe
Author: Walter Isaacson
My Review: Sounds cliched, but I have been reading this book for a long time and now that I finally finished it, I really do wish it went on further. The two most striking attributes about Einstein for me were A. his simplicity and B. his rebellious attitude. The narration shifts smoothly from his personal life to his professional projects to his public stature and to the events going on in the world around that time. For me,  there was a lot to learn from this book. It was definitely one of the best investments of my time.

Title: Preludes & Nocturnes (The Sandman, #1)

My Review: I read this book some while ago. Outliers contains well researched and though provoking ideas. Malcolm Gladwell uses a lot of examples to prove his point.. a style that is typical of most non fiction books. But reading through those stories was still a breeze.

Title: India After Gandhi: The History of the World's Largest Democracy
Author: Ramachandra Guha
My Review: A must read for every fan of history. Our school history books end after 1947. But this book gives you amazing insights into the big, and small, events post independence. It is paced like a thriller. This is how all history books should be written.

My Review: A very well crafted short story. It keeps you engaged till the end. It's humour is based on absurd yet genuine human actions and emotions . The plot is quite simple but the narration and twists are really interesting. Overall, a pleasant read.

Title: Twenty-Six Men and a Girl
Author: Maxim Gorky
My Review: I was introduced to Russian literature through Tolstoy and after reading this book, I am already a fan. I plan to read a lot more of these short stories in the future.

Title: The Clash of Civilizations and the Remaking of World Order
Author: Samuel P. Huntington
My Review: The author tries to present an oversimplified view of the world with its various cultures and civilizations. He especially focuses on the conflict between the West on one hand and Islam and China on the other. There were however, a few inaccuracies and false generalizations, for eg., regarding the Hindu civilization. Overall, the book gives some useful insights into global politics, though the length could have been easily reduced.

Title: Tuesdays with Morrie
Author: Mitch Albom
My Review: This is one of those bestsellers that lack any content or novel ideas. It's filled with boring cliches and over the top preachiness. Although some may find it digestible, this was not my cup of tea.

Title: Jaya: An Illustrated Retelling of the Mahabharata
Author: Devdutt Pattanaik
My Review: Thoroughly entertaining book filled with interesting anecdotes. The book presents a refreshing perspective on Mahabharat from what I had seen on TV or read in school textbooks.

Title: Batman: The Dark Knight Returns
Author: Frank Miller
My Review: Batman returns several years after his retirement to fight crime once again. It explores the psyche of Bruce Wayne in great detail.

Title: Batman: Year One
Author: Frank Miller
Additional Authors: David Mazzucchelli, Richmond Lewis, Todd Klein, Dennis O'Neil
My Review: Frank Miller's Batman : Year One is a must read for every fan. The book tells the story of the initial days of Bruce Wayne / Batman. It shares some similarities with the movie The Dark Knight Begins but it adds several other interesting details as well.

Title: So Good They Can't Ignore You: Why Skills Trump Passion in the Quest for Work You Love
Author: Cal Newport
My Review: Amazing. Must read for every young professional.

Title: Choose Yourself: Be Happy, Make Millions, Live the Dream
Author: James Altucher
My Review: I got to know about this through Quora. One of the better self help / motivational books I've read.

Title: Zero to One: Notes on Startups, or How to Build the Future
Author: Peter Thiel
My Review: This is more like a classroom lecture where Peter Thiel lists down 7-8 trends he sees in the startup ecosystem and then elaborates on them. Not a bad read. You can find some really good nuggets of wisdom in this book.

Title: Start-up Nation: The Story of Israel's Economic Miracle
Author: Dan Senor
My Review: The authors try to identify the reasons behind the success of Israelis in the startup world. An interesting read for future entrepreneurs.

Title: American Gods (American Gods, #1)
Author: Neil Gaiman
My Review: The storyline was pretty interesting and it kept me on the edge until the end. However, the climax was not so satisfying. Neil Gaiman is a great entertainer and he brings a lot of gore and edgy characters into this book.

Title: Veronika Decides to Die
Author: Paulo Coelho
My Review: Although the storyline is not very strong, yet it gives a good portayal of the life inside a mental asylum. It does give a rather good understanding of what can make a sane person go insane.

Title: Animal Farm
Author: George Orwell
Additional Authors: Boris Grabnar, Celâl Üster, Peter Škerl
My Review: It gives you an amazing perspective on political ideologies. Though there are certain generalizations, yet it is a fascinating take on history. A must read for anyone interested in politics.

Title: The Kreutzer Sonata
Author: Leo Tolstoy
My Review: Brilliantly written short story. It can make your skin crawl. Pretty accurate depiction of human emotions.

Title: The Doll's House (The Sandman, #2)
Author: Neil Gaiman
Additional Authors: Steve Parkhouse, Chris Bachalo, Michael Zulli, Mike Dringenberg, Malcolm Jones III, Todd Klein, Clive Barker

Title: Screw It, Let's Do It: Lessons In Life
Author: Richard Branson

Title: The Secret of the Nagas (Shiva Trilogy #2)
Author: Amish Tripathi

Title: 2 States: The Story of My Marriage
Author: Chetan Bhagat

Title: A Roller Coaster Ride
Author: Saumil Shrivastava
My Review: A total waste of time.

Author: Douglas Adams
